04297nam a22004935i 9780804780711DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047807117 a10.1515/97808047807112doi  a(DE-B1597)564743  a(OCoLC)1178768917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aUG447.8b.S585 2011eb 7aPOL0010002bisacsh04a327.1 745095672221 aSmithson, Amy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGerm Gambits :bThe Bioweapons Dilemma, Iraq and Beyond /cAmy Smithson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. UNSCOM's Inception and Infancy -- t2. UNSCOM's Initial Biological Inspections -- t3. From Hiatus to the Hunt -- t4. UNSCOM Shreds Iraq's Cover Stories -- t5. Defection and Artifice -- t6. Inspections in a Fact-Free Zone -- t7. Tentacles and Disintegration -- t8. Lessons Experienced I: Inspection Prerequisites -- t9. Lessons Experienced II: Sharpening the Tools of Inspection -- t10. Gambits Present and Future -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArms control and nonproliferation treaties are among the fingers in the dike preventing the unthinkable nuclear, biological, and chemical catastrophe. For decades the ability to ascertain whether states are hiding germ weapons programs has been nonexistent because the 1975 bioweapons ban has no inspection measures. Yet, in 1995 a small United Nations inspection corps pulled off a spectacular verification feat in the face of concerted resistance from Iraq's Saddam Hussein and popular skepticism that it was even possible to conduct effective biological inspections. Working from sketchy intelligence-and hampered by the Iraqis' extensive concealment and deception measures-the inspectors busted open Iraq's cover stories and wrested a confession of biowarfare agent production from Baghdad. This rigorously researched book tells that compelling story through the firsthand accounts of the inspectors who, with a combination of intrepidness, ingenuity, and a couple of lucky breaks, took the lid off Iraq's bioweapons program and pulled off an improbable victory for peace and international security. The book concludes by drawing lessons from this experience that should be applied to help arrest future bioweapons programs, by placing the Iraq bioweapons saga in the context of other manmade biological risks, and by making recommendations to reduce those risks. While written as an engaging, analytical historical narrative that explains what the biological inspectors knew, when and how they knew it, and how they outmaneuvered the Iraqis, this book's real contributions are the inspectors' blueprint to "get it right" with regard to the verification challenges associated with the bioweapons ban, and the author's roadmap to address the overall biological threats facing the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBiological arms controlxVerificationzIraqxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Arms Control.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478071140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804780711.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles